427
46:32.730 --> 46:41.490
as projective measurements. By the way, this degeneracy only happens in the simplified description
of quantum information.

428
46:41.490 --> 46:49.290
When we describe quantum
states using density matrices, as we will do in the
third unit of the series, we will have a unique
matrix representation

429
46:49.290 --> 46:56.310
for every quantum state. The issue of global phases
simply doesn't arise in the general description
of quantum information.

430
46:56.310 --> 47:04.470
It's one more appealing aspect
of the general description of quantum information,
which I keep alluding to, but regardless, global
phases won't bother us

431
47:04.470 --> 47:10.020
because we can just exercise
our freedom to ignore them.

432
47:10.020 --> 47:15.390
Here's a very quick
example just to make sure the notion of a global phase is clear.

433
47:15.390 --> 47:25.740
If we have a minus state, and negative one times a minus state, then these two states
differ by a global phase, and in particular we have
alpha equals negative one.

434
47:25.740 --> 47:31.740
On the other hand, if we have a plus state and a minus state, then we don't have two states
that differ by a global phase.

435
47:31.740 --> 47:36.300
These are orthogonal vectors, so they're linearly independent.

436
47:36.300 --> 47:42.960
To say that two quantum state vectors differ by a global phase
is equivalent to saying that the vectors are linearly dependent,

437
47:42.960 --> 47:46.920
so certainly these vectors
don't differ by a global phase.

438
47:46.920 --> 47:54.600
It's true that the only difference is that this plus sign
turns into this minus sign, but that's what we call a
relative phase difference.

439
47:54.600 --> 48:00.270
That's different from a global phase because we're not
multiplying the entire vector by a complex number.

440
48:00.270 --> 48:07.050
And this is consistent with the fact that we can tell the difference
between these states, in particular, if we
apply a Hadamard operation

441
48:07.050 --> 48:13.470
and then measure, we'll see a zero if the
state was a plus state and a one if the state was a minus state.

442
48:13.470 --> 48:20.340
The next limitation of quantum information that we'll see in this lesson
is the no-cloning theorem.

443
48:20.340 --> 48:27.600
Here's one statement of
the no-cloning theorem and this particular
statement of the theorem is pretty concrete and specific,

444
48:27.600 --> 48:33.720
which will make it easier to talk about. There are other more general ways to formulate the no-cloning theorem,

445
48:33.720 --> 48:37.575
but we'll focus on this one for now.

446
48:37.575 --> 48:42.030
We assume that we have two systems X and Y which have the same classical state set.

447
48:42.030 --> 48:47.700
which consists of the
integer from zero to D-1 where D is at least two.

448
48:47.700 --> 48:54.390
It's not really important what names the classical states have, but by choosing these names it'll help to keep things simple.

449
48:54.390 --> 49:03.150
What's most important
here is that there are at least two different classical
states, so in other words, we're not worrying about the
trivial and uninteresting case

450
49:03.150 --> 49:06.870
where we only have one classical state.

451
49:06.870 --> 49:15.600
What the theorem says is that there's no unitary operation U that we can apply to X, Y so that if we initialize
Y to the zero state,

452
49:15.600 --> 49:21.540
we effectively copy or clone
arbitrary quantum states of X.

453
49:21.540 --> 49:28.950
If we take a look at this
expression right here in isolation, what it says is that for all choices of a quantum state vector Psi of X,

454
49:28.950 --> 49:37.770
applying U to Psi tensored
with the zero state, gives us Psi tensor Psi, or in other words two
independent copies of Psi,

455
49:37.770 --> 49:45.510
so that's what it would mean if we could clone quantum
states and what the theorem says is that this is not possible.

456
49:45.510 --> 49:54.840
You can think about this
in terms of circuits and what the theorem says is
that you'll never be able to come up with a gate or a circuit
that works as you see here.

457
49:54.840 --> 50:02.580
Where one copy of the state Psi comes in along with a collection
of initialized Qubits and two copies of Psi are produced.

458
50:02.580 --> 50:09.870
You can do this for certain
choices of the state Psi, but you can never come up with
a circuit that works this way for every quantum state Psi,

459
50:09.870 --> 50:14.730
and that's what the theorem says.

460
50:14.730 --> 50:22.260
It's quite easy to prove
this theorem, in fact, it essentially boils down to the fact that the transformation we're
looking for isn't linear,

461
50:22.260 --> 50:28.350
but unitary operations are
linear, so it just can't work.

462
50:28.350 --> 50:32.100
Here's an argument in a bit more detail.

463
50:32.100 --> 50:40.050
Suppose that we have a unitary operation U that clones the standard basis
states, Ket 0 and Ket one.

464
50:40.050 --> 50:47.790
We know that the classical
states zero and one must belong to our classical state set because D is at least two.

465
50:47.790 --> 50:54.390
But this means by linearity
that if X is in a plus state, which we can write like this,

466
50:54.390 --> 50:59.490
then the result is this linear combination of these two states right here.

467
50:59.490 --> 51:06.030
However, that's not the right behavior. The requirement on U is that
U cloned is a plus state,

468
51:06.030 --> 51:10.590
which means that we have to
have this equation right here being satisfied.

469
51:10.590 --> 51:18.420
These two states aren't the
same and so it doesn't work and that's all there is to it.

470
51:18.420 --> 51:22.530
Just a few additional remarks
about the no-cloning theorem.

471
51:22.530 --> 51:26.850
First, this statement of the
no-cloning theorem is absolute in some sense.

472
51:26.850 --> 51:33.150
It simply says that a unitary operation U that works exactly like
this doesn't exist.

473
51:33.150 --> 51:40.200
So you might ask whether
or not there exists unitary operation U that
does this approximately with respect to some way of describing

